+# Phase 14A — Mobile & Rapid Capture Architecture Boundaries
+
+## Goal
+
+Define Mobile & Rapid Capture architecture boundaries before implementing aggressive mobile UX optimization, offline behavior, or rapid operational capture runtime systems.
+
+This phase is architecture/review focused only: no offline sync/runtime behavior, no push notifications, no mobile-native packaging/runtime behavior, no aggressive Feed/Inbox mobile experiences, and no guardian-facing mobile workflows are introduced.
+
+## Scope Guardrails (enforced)
+
+- Do not implement offline sync/runtime behavior.
+- Do not implement push notifications.
+- Do not implement mobile-native packaging/runtime behavior.
+- Do not implement aggressive Feed/Inbox mobile experiences.
+- Do not implement guardian-facing mobile workflows.
+- Keep this phase architecture/review focused.
+- Preserve organization scoping and authorization behavior.
+- Do not introduce new major dependencies.
+
+## Reviewed Runtime Baseline (Arcs 8–13)
+
+### Operational and intelligence-awareness work reviewed
+
+- Arc 8 workflow continuity/review usability (`PHASE_8F`, `PHASE_8H`, `PHASE_8N`) established human-driven operational review flows and continuity links across events, attendance, notes, and tasks.
+- Arc 9/10 authorization and Entry wrapper work kept `ObservationNote`/`FollowUpTask` authoritative, with additive read-only `EntryRuntimeRef` traceability.
+- Arc 11 friction/stability work (`PHASE_11B`, `PHASE_11C`) tightened attendance validation and pilot-safe workflow continuity.
+- Arc 12 communication-awareness work (`PHASE_12A`–`PHASE_12E`) separated awareness metadata from messaging/delivery and deferred Inbox/Feed runtime behavior.
+- Arc 13 intelligence-awareness work (`PHASE_13A`–`PHASE_13E`) added deterministic read-only staff awareness layers while keeping AI/recommendation/automation/Feed/Inbox deferred.
+
+### Current operational capture and review patterns
+
+| Workflow area | Current implemented pattern | Mobile/rapid-capture friction signals |
+|---|---|---|
+| Attendance capture | Event detail attendance workflow posts to `/events/[eventId]/attendance`; roster-season validation and explicit error redirects preserve correctness. | Capture is event-detail anchored and form-heavy; repeated person/status entry and validation round-trips can slow sideline use. |
+| Observation capture | `/notes/new` + `/notes/create` supports optional person/team/event linkage with staff-only gating and org validation. | Multi-field context selection and redirect-based error handling increase taps and context switching on small screens. |
+| Follow-up creation | `/tasks/new` + `/tasks/create` links assignee, source note/event, due date, visibility-safe linkage checks. | Task creation requires multiple selections and optional context reconciliation, increasing mobile completion friction. |
+| Operational review workflows | `/dashboard` aggregates scoped readiness/review cues, history, and links into existing event/note/task/team workflows. | Fast scan/act loops depend on navigation across several pages; mobile flow compression is not yet optimized. |
+| Event workflows | `/events/new`, `/events/[eventId]`, RSVP/attendance links, note/task continuity links preserve event-centered operations. | Event detail is information-dense; action controls are present but not tuned yet for rapid one-handed operational capture. |
+| FieldOps workflows | `/field-ops/bookings/new`, create precheck route, and approval decision route preserve scoped validation and explicit approval policy checks. | Booking request capture has many optional context fields and validation dependencies that can be slow on mobile. |
+
+## Mobile & Rapid Capture Concepts (Architecture)
+
+### Rapid operational capture
+
+Rapid capture means reducing interaction cost for existing authoritative workflows (attendance, note, task, booking decision/capture) without changing authority models, authorization boundaries, or introducing asynchronous/offline write engines.
+
+### Mobile workflow priorities
+
+1. Preserve in-context capture from current operational surfaces (event, dashboard, tasks, notes, FieldOps).
+2. Reduce tap count and context re-entry for high-frequency actions.
+3. Keep operator intent explicit before any state-changing write.
+4. Keep all capture paths staff-scoped and organization-scoped.
+
+### Reduced-click workflow design goals
+
+- Promote context-prefilled flows from existing links/query params.
+- Minimize field duplication when event/team/person context is already known.
+- Keep validation feedback immediate and explicit without weakening existing guardrails.
+
+### Operational context preservation
+
+- Event-linked, team-linked, and note/task relationship context must remain visible at capture time.
+- Capture acceleration must not hide source context or relationship constraints that prevent ambiguous writes.
+
+### Low-friction data entry
+
+- Favor compact, deterministic capture surfaces for current staff workflows.
+- Prioritize ergonomics for short, high-frequency entries (attendance status, note summaries, task follow-ups, booking request metadata).
+
+### Operational speed considerations
+
+- Prioritize speed for current read→decide→capture loops on dashboard/event/task/note/FieldOps surfaces.
+- Keep speed optimizations strictly within existing runtime authority and authorization checks.
+
+### Offline/runtime considerations (deferred architecture boundary)
+
+- Mobile optimization work may define offline risk handling expectations but must not implement offline write queues, sync engines, conflict resolvers, or stale-cache authority behavior in this phase.
+
+## Boundary Definitions (Must Remain Separate)
+
+### 1) Mobile optimization vs offline runtime
+
+- **Mobile optimization:** responsive UX/layout and interaction-cost reduction for online, server-authoritative workflows.
+- **Offline runtime:** local persistence, deferred writes, sync/conflict resolution, stale-state reconciliation.
+- Phase 14A allows only architecture definition for offline concerns, not implementation.
+
+### 2) Rapid capture vs Feed/Inbox
+
+- **Rapid capture:** direct completion of existing workflow actions (attendance/note/task/booking) with lower interaction cost.
+- **Feed/Inbox:** stream/triage runtime models with separate routing and ownership semantics.
+- Phase 14A rapid capture must not evolve into Feed/Inbox runtime behavior.
+
+### 3) Operational awareness vs messaging
+
+- **Operational awareness:** read-only staff visibility derived from authorized operational data.
+- **Messaging/notifications:** delivery systems, recipient targeting, dispatch, acknowledgment, and channel runtime.
+- Mobile awareness improvements must not introduce messaging/notification runtime behavior.
+
+### 4) Mobile workflow acceleration vs automation
+
+- **Acceleration:** faster staff-driven actions with explicit user intent.
+- **Automation:** system-triggered writes, escalations, or autonomous workflow execution.
+- Phase 14A allows acceleration only; automation remains deferred.
+
+## Mobile/Capture Risk Areas
+
+1. **Accidental operational actions**  
+   Faster mobile controls can increase mistaken submissions if confirmation/context cues are weak.
+
+2. **Incomplete capture**  
+   Reduced-friction forms may encourage partial submissions that miss required operational context.
+
+3. **Authorization leakage on mobile surfaces**  
+   Mobile-specific summaries or shortcuts can leak out-of-scope data if staff/org checks are bypassed.
+
+4. **Operational ambiguity**  
+   Compressed interfaces can hide event/team/source-link context and cause incorrect note/task/attendance linkage.
+
+5. **Stale/offline data concerns**  
+   Mobile users in unstable connectivity contexts may act on stale state unless runtime boundaries stay server-authoritative.
+
+## Do Not Implement Yet
+
+- Full offline sync.
+- Push notifications.
+- Native mobile apps.
+- Guardian-facing mobile runtime.
+- Mobile Feed/Inbox systems.
+
+## Safe First Mobile Slice (Recommendation)
+
+Start with a **staff-only mobile web capture acceleration slice** on existing pages:
+
+- attendance quick-capture ergonomics within event workflows,
+- note/task rapid-capture entry improvements with context prefill from existing links,
+- dashboard-to-capture navigation compression for unresolved operational items,
+- FieldOps request/decision form ergonomics for active staff workflows.
+
+Safety boundaries for this slice:
+
+- no new authority models,
+- no offline write behavior,
+- no messaging/push,
+- no Feed/Inbox runtime semantics,
+- no guardian-facing mobile runtime surfaces.
+
+## Blocking Before Offline/Mobile Runtime Checklist
+
+- [ ] Define explicit stale-state UX contract (what users see when mobile data age is unknown).
+- [ ] Define authoritative-write policy for intermittent connectivity (what is blocked vs deferred).
+- [ ] Define conflict-resolution policy for concurrent edits and delayed submissions.
+- [ ] Define mobile-specific authorization verification points for every capture surface.
+- [ ] Define audit requirements for mobile-originated operational actions.
+- [ ] Define failure/retry semantics for mobile submission errors without silent data loss.
+- [ ] Complete cross-role/cross-scope validation matrix for mobile surfaces.
+- [ ] Confirm guardian-facing mobile runtime policy and consent boundaries before any exposure.
+- [ ] Confirm Feed/Inbox runtime dependencies remain blocked.
+- [ ] Confirm push/notification delivery architecture is separately gated and approved.
+
+## Validation and Compliance Confirmation
+
+- Architecture review reflects current implemented runtime/auth behavior across:
+  - `getOrganizationScope()` organization boundary enforcement,
+  - staff-only/scoped operational surface gating,
+  - existing event/attendance/note/task/FieldOps create/update route validations.
+- No runtime offline/mobile-native behavior was added.
+- No Feed/Inbox runtime behavior was added.
+- No messaging/notification behavior was added.
+- Runtime code was not changed in this phase; additional typecheck/build reruns after documentation edits were not required.
+
